                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t17711023-7-off28 t17711023-7-crimeloc30"></join>. On the 14th of August my servant came to the coffee-house to me, and informed me I had been robbed. I was with my family at my country-house at Hackney I went home and found every lock broke, and the things gone that are mentioned in the indictment; I went and informed Sir 
               <persName id="t17711023-7-person88">
                  John
                   Fielding
               <interp inst="t17711023-7-person88" type="surname" value="Fielding"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17711023-7-person88" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17711023-7-person88" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             of what I had lost. A few days afterwards some silk was produced, of my wife's own embroidering, which was found on the prisoner, as I understand; about a fortnight after that another bundle of things was produced, which are my property; I was in my house on Friday the 9th, every thing was safe then.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17711023-7-person89">
                  Samuel
                   Johnson
               <interp inst="t17711023-7-person89" type="surname" value="Johnson"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17711023-7-person89" type="given" value="Samuel"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17711023-7-person89" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live at Canterbury. On Wednesday or Thursday in the first week in September, the prisoner called at my house, and asked me if I wanted two chintz counterpanes; he said they were very fine and handsome, upon which I desired to see them; he brought them soon afterwards; I perceived they were black, and appeared as if they had been used a good while; he asked four guineas and a half for them, at last we agreed for two guineas; he then asked me if I wanted a silk waistcoat, he brought me two remnants of silk, I gave him eighteen shillings for them. On the Monday following Sir 
               <persName id="t17711023-7-person90">
                  John
                   Fielding
               <interp inst="t17711023-7-person90" type="surname" value="Fielding"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17711023-7-person90" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17711023-7-person90" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            's people had took up the prisoner at Canterbury, and they called upon me; I immediately produced the things I had bought of him; (the goods produced, and deposed to by the prosecutor.)</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17711023-7-person91">
                  Sarah
                   Levi
               <interp inst="t17711023-7-person91" type="surname" value="Levi"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17711023-7-person91" type="given" value="Sarah"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17711023-7-person91" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live at Canterbury. The prisoner came to me on Tuesday about six weeks ago, and asked me if I would buy some cloaths<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="177110230005"></xptr> of him; I have lived at Canterbury sixteen years, and deal in old cloaths; he first brought me five shirts, which, after hawking them about some time, I sold for him at six shillings a-piece; then he gave me a check silk sack and petticoat, I sold it for him at a coffee-house, and after that I sold a grey silk gown full of spots for a guinea and a half, and a sort of a white gown for a guinea and a half, and a damask curtain for twenty-five shillings, and an old pair of sheets for eight shillings; he told me he went to all the public sales in town, and bought a great many goods; I was from Monday till Friday in selling them. I went to the people I sold the things to and got them again, and brought them to Sir 
               <persName id="t17711023-7-person92">
                  John
                   Fielding
               <interp inst="t17711023-7-person92" type="surname" value="Fielding"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17711023-7-person92" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17711023-7-person92" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            's, (the goods produced, and deposed to by the prosecutor.)</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence.</p>
               <p>I never sold or delivered any things to Levi. I have travelled that country these twenty years; the things Mr. Johnson produced I bought of a Frenchman near Canterbury; I gave fifty shillings for them, and sold them to Mr. Johnson for three pounds; there was a Scotchman present when I bought them.</p>
               <p>For the Prisoner:</p>
               <p>Saunders Aaron. I have known the prisoner upwards of twenty years; he has bought several hundreds of snuff of my master, and paid very honestly for his goods; I never heard any bad character of him.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17711023-7-person93">
                  James
                   Goldsborough
               <interp inst="t17711023-7-person93" type="surname" value="Goldsborough"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17711023-7-person93" type="given" value="James"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17711023-7-person93" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a watch-spring maker, and live at No. 5, in Union-court, Holborn; I have known him nine years, he used to sell snuff and rhubarb, he bears a good character; I never heard any thing to the contrary.</p>
